BT /F2 14 Tf 54 712.0 Td (CHAPTER 1: UNDERSTANDING ANXIETY) Tj ET
54 684.0 m 558 684.0 l 0.5 w S
BT /F2 12 Tf 54 658.2 Td (What Is Anxiety?) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 630.4 Td (Anxiety is your body's natural response to perceived threats or danger. It is a complex) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 616.4 Td (combination of physical sensations, thoughts, and behaviors that evolved to protect us) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 602.4 Td (from harm. While some anxiety is normal and even helpful, excessive or chronic anxiety can) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 588.4 Td (interfere with daily life, relationships, work performance, and overall well-being.) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 564.6 Td (Understanding anxiety is the first step toward managing it effectively. When you) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 550.6 Td (understand what is happening in your brain and body during an anxiety response, you gain) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 536.6 Td (the power to intervene and redirect that response in healthier ways.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 54 506.8 Td (The Anxiety Cycle) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 479.0 Td (Anxiety operates in a predictable cycle that reinforces itself over time. Understanding) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 465.0 Td (this cycle gives you multiple intervention points where you can break the pattern:) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 441.2 Td (- TRIGGER: An event, thought, or sensation that activates anxiety) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 427.2 Td (- THOUGHT: An interpretation of the trigger \(often catastrophic or distorted\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 413.2 Td (- PHYSICAL RESPONSE: Body sensations like racing heart, sweating, tension) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 399.2 Td (- EMOTIONAL RESPONSE: Feelings of fear, dread, panic, or overwhelm) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 385.2 Td (- BEHAVIORAL RESPONSE: Avoidance, escape, reassurance-seeking, or safety behaviors) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 371.2 Td (- REINFORCEMENT: Short-term relief from avoidance strengthens the anxiety cycle) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 347.4 Td (Each time you avoid something that triggers anxiety, your brain learns that the trigger is) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 333.4 Td (genuinely dangerous. This makes the anxiety stronger next time. Breaking this cycle) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 319.4 Td (requires gradually facing fears while using coping strategies to manage discomfort.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 54 289.6 Td (Types of Anxiety Disorders) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 261.8 Td (While this workbook addresses general anxiety management skills, it helps to understand) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 247.8 Td (the different presentations anxiety can take:) Tj ET
BT /F2 11 Tf 54 220.0 Td (Generalized Anxiety Disorder \(GAD\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 204.0 Td (Characterized by excessive, uncontrollable worry about multiple areas of life including) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 190.0 Td (work, health, family, money, and everyday matters. People with GAD often describe feeling) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 176.0 Td (worried most of the time and find it difficult to relax or stop their mind from racing.) Tj ET
BT /F2 11 Tf 54 148.2 Td (Social Anxiety Disorder) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 132.2 Td (Intense fear of social situations where you might be judged, embarrassed, or rejected.) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 118.2 Td (This can range from specific fears like public speaking to generalized discomfort in most) Tj ET
BT /F1 10 Tf 54 104.2 Td (social interactions.) Tj ET
endstream
endobj
